对象。学科教学知识的本质就是教学活动各要素之间的相对稳定联系。它是经过教师个人检验而积累的实践性知识。具有高度的情景依赖性、个体依赖性、对象依赖性以及时效性，活动系统各个要素的关系必须放在有意义的活动情景理解，同样学科教学知识也必须放在具体的教学情境中应用。\n\n\n将冰冷的科学知识还原为科学家火热的思考\n\n数学教育专家弗赖登塔尔曾说：“没有一种数学思想，以它被发现时的那个样子公开发表出来。一种问题被解决后，相应地发展成一种形式化的技巧，结果把求解过程丢到一边，使火热的发明变成了冰冷的美丽。”\n\n\n我国教学设计研究40年审思与展望\n1921年就提出了教学设计一词，【国外要找这个词，估计肯定更早，所以谁早没那么重要，重要的是用得好】【这个第一个使用教学设计的，肯定是从课堂教学的朴素视角，而不是教育技术学的视角】【题目的中研究好像不太够，实践差不多】【敢用我国二字也有点大，最重要的是它并没有考虑不同学科，比如生物学或者教育技术学】\n\n教学设计是对如何开展教学的规划和分析。这类研究又可以分为两种基本形式:一种是基于具体教学内容的教案或教学设计思路分析;另一种是在经验基础上进行的脱离具体内容的一般性分析。\n\n\n生物学教学设计发展40年审视与展望\n1984-2020\n\n当你往前看时，你需要的是概率论作为指导；当你往后看时，你需要的是还原论、因果论的指导；当你驻足当下时，你需要目的论的指导。\n\n人类是自然之镜。\n\n后现代主义是要强迫科学家站队吗？要知道不站队也是一种站队。科学家从来没有说自己是客观立场，他们只是尽量避免偏见。\n\n\n\nBrown, A. H., & Green, T. D. The essentials of instructional design: Connecting fundamental principles with process and practice(Third Edition). Routledge.(2016).\n\nThe key procedures within the ID process—learner analysis, task analysis, needs analysis, developing goals and objectives, organizing instruction, developing instructional activities, assessing learner achievement, and evaluating the success of the instructional design\n\n教学设计过程包含：学习者分析、任务分析、需要分析、制定目标、组织教学、开发教学活动、评估学习成就、评估教学设计\n\nTrilling, B., & Fadel, C. 21st Century Skills: Learning for Life in Our Times. San Francisco, CA: John Wiley & Sons,2009:45-60.\n\n\nNo matter which established model one refers to, there are generally three phases to the ID process: \nexamination of the situation (needs, task, and learner analysis); \ncreating instruction (planning, creating, and implementing the intervention); \nand evaluating the effect of the instruction.\n\n无论是哪一个模型，大体都包含3个阶段：检验教学情境、设计教学活动、评估教学效果。\n\nWhat Is Instructional Design?\n“The purpose of any design activity is to devise optimal means to achieve desired ends.”\n\n任何设计活动的目的都是设计出达到所需目标的最佳方法。\n\n—Charles Reigeluth, 1983\n\n\nBy 1915, the application of scientific methods to the solution of educational problems had won out among the leaders in American education, setting the stage for the develop- ment of Dewey’s linking science, which scholars such as Snellbecker (1974) suggest is the discipline of instructional design.\n教学设计作为一个学科\n\n\nAccording to Smith and Ragan (2005), instructional design may be currently defined as “the systematic and reflective process of translating principles of learning and instruction into plans for instructional materials, activities, information resources, and evaluation” (p. 4).\n现在的定义\n教学设计是将教与学的原则转化成教学计划、材料、活动、信息资源和评价的系统性、反思性过程。\n\n\nThe Applied Research Laboratory at Penn State University is attributed with develop- ing a four-part definition of instructional design (University of Michigan, 2003):\n\n\np6\nUniversity of Michigan. (2003). Definitions of instructional design. Adapted from “Training and instructional design,” Applied Research Laboratory, Penn State University (1996). Ann Arbor: The University of Michigan. Retrieved from www.umich.edu/~ed626/define.html.\n\n教学设计作为一个过程\n教学设计作为一门学科\n教学设计作为一项研究\n教学设计作为现实存在\n\n教学设计鼓励应用相关研究成果，这些研究包括人是如何思考的，如何学习学习，可用的通讯技术、分析方法等。\n\n\n教学设计就是应用这些知识，通过活动和环境的创造学习有效发生的契机。\n\nHokanson and Gibbons (2014) observe, “Design involves dealing with uncertainties, and designers must not only learn to deal with uncertainty but embrace and use uncertainty as a tool to propel optimal design solutions” (p. 11). \nHokanson, B., & Gibbons, A. (Eds). (2014). Design in educational technology: Design thinking, design process, and the design studio. Cham, Switzerland: Springer International Publishing.\n设计涉及不确定性的处理，设计师不仅必须学会处理不确定性，还必须拥抱并使用不确定性作为工具来逼近最佳设计解决方案（第11页）。\n\n教学设计的三步骤：\na three-step process:\n1 Analyze the situation to determine what instruction is necessary and what steps need to be taken to deliver that instruction.\n2 Produce and implement the instructional design.\n3 Evaluate the results of implementing the instructional design.\n\n分析问题情境\n设计并执行教学设计\n评估教学设计执行结果\n\n\nMerrill (2002, pp. 44–45) suggests there are five basic principles that hold true for the design of any instruction. The first principles of instruction state that learning is promoted when:\n• learners are engaged in solving real-world problems;\n• existing knowledge is activated as a foundation for new knowledge;\n• new knowledge is demonstrated to the learner;\n• new knowledge is applied by the learner;\n• new knowledge is integrated into the learner’s world.\n\n学习者参与现实世界的问题解决\n已有知识被激活作为新知识的基础\n新知识展示给学习者\n新知识被学习者应用\n新知识整合到学习者的体系中\n\n\n教学系统设计，课程层面，关注可见学习目标。【可见与不可见是一对矛盾，需要协调起来，不能走极端】\nThe ISD [instructional systems design] model begins at the curriculum level with analysis of content, definition of overall objectives, delineation of sequences and sub- sequences of the curriculum. It proceeds with the selection of instructional methods and media, designing individual lessons to enhance learner mastery of the objectives, developing delivery systems for the individual lessons, and ends with evaluation of the lessons and the entire instructional system. Evaluation in ISD emphasizes measurement of observable target behaviors.\n(Alessi and Trollip, 2001, p. 18)\n\n\n后现代教学设计立场\nA postmodern approach to instructional design recognizes that the instructional designer must take four societal factors into account:\n\n课堂权威的没落\n1 Society is past the point where there are a limited number of authorities available to a classroom student. The modern classroom had two authoritative sources: the teacher and the textbook. This situation no longer exists because students have access to many other sources, including the internet, television, and, in some cases, friends and family who are more educated than the teacher is (Hlynka, 1995).\n\n单一培养目标和课程已经无法满足多样化的教育需要\n2 No longer can there be an agreed-upon, single type of well-educated individual. Determining a curriculum and including all important artistic and scientific works that would be appropriate for all individuals is impossible.\n\n传统线性教学程序与建构主义不相符\n3 The currently popular cognitive paradigm—constructivism—does not recognize or advocate a traditional, linear educational sequence. With information available from a variety of sources outside the classroom, learners will inevitably deviate from a lin- ear instructional model by observing and reacting to other examples, non-examples, and divergent examples of the concepts they study in school.\n\n唯一、客观真理不复存在。\n4 No single, objective truth exists. Truth is a construct that is based on an individual’s personal interpretation or on the consensus of a group of people for their purposes. The truth—also known as “the right answer”—may change depending on the context and the individuals involved.\n\n\n建构主义学习环境特征：情境化学习；社会协商；多元化视角和表达方式；学习的自主权；对知识建构过程的自我意识。\nDriscoll (2004) summarizes the conditions necessary for learning in a constructivist environment:\n• embedded learning in complex, realistic, and relevant environments;\n• providing for social negotiation as an integral part of learning;\n• supporting multiple perspectives and the use of multiple modes of representation;\n• encouraging ownership in learning; and\n• nurturing self-awareness of the knowledge construction process.\n(pp. 382–383)\n\n教学设计的9要素：定义问题；学习者分析；内容分析；设定教学目标；设计内容序列；设计教学策略；设计开发教学活动；开发评估工具；选择教学资源。\nThe Kemp, Morrison, and Ross plan (see Figure 1.2) is expressed as nine elements:\n1 Identify instructional problems and specify goals for designing instruction.\n2 Examine learner characteristics that will influence your instructional decisions.\n3 Identify subject content, and analyze task components related to stated goals and\npurposes.\n4 Specify the instructional objectives.\n5 Sequence content within each instructional unit for logical learning.\n6 Design instructional strategies so that each learner can master the objectives.\n7 Plan the instructional message and develop the instruction.\n8 Develop evaluation instruments to assess the objectives.\n9 Select resources to support instruction and learning activities.\n(Morrison, Ross, & Kemp, 2004, pp. 7–8)\n\n\n\n\n\n生物课教学设计的两个重要问题_陈松铨\n\n认清教学设计与教案的区别；教学设计应针对知识的类别\n\n教学设计与教案的关系 \n教学设计是对教学整体和教学全程的把握与战略决策。 对教师而言 ,教学设计就是根据国家的教育方针和教育在某个阶段所应培养的目标,在教育、教学理论的指导下 ,根据学生的身心特点、发展规律以及学习规律,切合实际情况决定教学的整体策略的过程。 它注重的是宏观的和共性化的问题。教案则应是在教学设计的引导下,结合不同班级的具体状况 ,为完成每节课必须实现的设计要求作可操作性的战术准备。它注重的是微观的和个性化的问题。\n\n【这个认识和叶丽新老师文章的题法完全相反】\n\n【中学老师的教学设计是从教育技术学借用过来的，因此理解完全不同，有的老师是从朴素的备课角度理解教学设计，有的老师则用教育技术学的教学系统设计，所以会有冲突。】\n\n\n\n浅谈教学设计方案_陈佳琳\n教学设计的类型和原则\n对教学设计进行了定义，同时也对教学设计的要素进行了概括。\n\n一节课的科学、高效率的教学设计方案，通常是在现代教学思想指导下，运用系统方法、兴趣教学法对教与学的行为进行设计。它是一个分析教与学的问题，设计解决问题的方法、方案，并在实施中加以评价、修正，使之达到教学优化的微观的教学过程的设计方案。\n\n\n主要内容是课题、课时、教学目标、教学的重点、难点、教学方法、教具 (包括学具 )、教学过程 (包括反馈检测题等 )、板书内容、补充教材、教材前后知识点的衔接、当今科技动态等 ,侧重把握教材的深度和广度。 其主要任务是: ( 1)教师完成对教材深度和广度的把握; ( 2)通过多年的备课、搜集和整理大量的信息 ,不断地补充同一问题的新知识、新进展 ,同时完成教师的知识更新和完善。\n\n表格式教案 这类教案多适用于有经验的老教师。主要内容有课题、课时、教学目标、教学的重点和难点、教具(包括学具 )、教学程序 (所有教具的操作顺序、教学方法的具体操作过程，学法指导的具体操作过程)、板书设计，侧重教法、学法的具体操作。\n\n【很有意思的是，不知道什么时候表格式的教学设计变成了教师和学生的双边活动。】\n\n\n课堂实录教案多采用优质课评选、公开课等。它是教学改革和教学研究的产物，是教师课堂具体实施教学过程的安排表或实录。主要内容有：课题、课时、教学目标、教学的重点和难点、教具 (及学具 )、教学过程、板书设计等 ，侧重于教学过程的具体安排。其中导言、知识的过渡、重点的教法、难点的学法指导、教具的选择和使用等将体现教师的教学特色、教改意识和教改的具体做法。主要任务是： (1)为各级领导、各类教师听课、评课提供参考资料； (2)为教师互相学习、交流经验进行教学改革和研究提供学习的材料。\n\n1. 科学性 教案中基本概念、基础理论、书面语表达要科学、严密、准确、精练。\n2. 目标性 每节课的教案中 ,教学目标必须具体、明确。 因为它决定了课堂教学的方向。\n3. 程序性 教案的设计 ,必须依据学生的认识水平、认识过程和认知规律 ,有序地编排教学内容和采用恰当的教学方法 ,又可供教与学的操作。\n4. 整体优化性 教案的设计中 ,必须认真把握在严格规定的时间内 ,将教学过程中的各个因素科学组合、优化设计 ,以达到最佳的教学效果。\n\n\n\n刍议生物课堂教学设计的原则_马爱君\n现行的教育设计理论认为, 所谓教学设计就是运用系统科学的方法,遵循生物教学过程和学生的认知规律，对教学活动进行系统规划的过程。\n\n原则：系统、主题、思想、科学、现代性\n\n试论生物课堂教学设计的科学性_袁维新\n试论生物学课堂教学设计的美学原则_袁维新\n\n【中学生物学教学论，是否有教学设计的定义？】要查一下\n\n顶层设计：课程纲领和课标\n中层设计：教科书和教学活动\n底层设计：教室、教具和课表\n\n\n\n生物学教学设计的发展和演变：反思与展望\n\n\nBellotti, F., Berta, R. & De Gloria, A. (2010). Designing Effective Serious Games: Opportunities and Challenges for Research. International Journal of Emerging Technologies in Learning (iJET), 5(2010),. Kassel, Germany: International Journal of Emerging Technology in Learning. Retrieved July 2, 2020 from https://www.learntechlib.org/p/44949/.\n\n\nMorrison, G. R., Ross, S. M., Kalman, H. K., & Kemp, J. E.Designing Effective Instruction.John Wiley & Sons.(2013)P237-239\n\n\n\nThese ideas, worked on throughout the 1950s and 1960s, were solidified in instructional design models during the 1970s. The influential models of Dick and Carey (1978), Gagné and Briggs (1974), Kemp (1971), and others were published during this period. Interest in instructional design flourished as the military, business, and industry embraced instructional design methods to enhance training. Instructional design models expanded to include needs assessment.\n\nKemp (1971)就已经开始提出教学设计的模式了\n\n大体上教学设计，\n\n三段：ADE\n五段：ADDIE\n九段：问题确定、学习者分析、内容分析、学习需要分析、\n\n\n\nThere is an old saying that if you don’t know where you are going, any road will get you there. This is a fine philosophy if you are spending the summer between your junior and senior year “experiencing” Europe or if you have embarked on an Australian “walk-about,” but when you are developing train- ing programs it leaves a lot to be desired.\n\nPiskurich, G. M. (2015). Rapid instructional design. Wiley.\n\n这本书写得很风趣\n\n作者的写作风格可以学习的呀\n\n用的最多的还是ADDIE但是，这其实是一个一般模型，所有的设计都可以这样做。\n\n包括斯坦福的模型，EDIPT，同情、定义、创新、原型、测试\n\n设计思维\nAlthough there are many models of design thinking, one of the most popular models is attributed to Stanford University’s d.school (Stanford University Institute of Design, 2018).3 The model uses the stages of empathize, define, ideate, prototype, and test as an organizational scheme (see Figure 1.1).\n• Empathize: Understanding the user’s experience is recognized as key to design thinking, so it all starts with developing a deep understanding of the people for whom the products or processes will be designed.\n\n• Define: Using the information gained in the empathize stage, the problem is stated in terms of the users’ needs, their problems, and the designer’s insights.\n\n• Ideate: Once the problem has been defined in a human-centered way, designers brainstorm multiple ideas for innovative solutions, often through challenging common assumptions.\n\n• Prototype: In the prototype phase, designers select the most promising ideas to explore through the creation of inexpensive scaled-down versions of the product or experience. Sketches, scenarios, cardboard mock- ups, draft interfaces, role plays, storyboards, and slide shows, as well as more developed working prototypes, can all be used to illustrate the user’s experience.\n\n• Test: Here, one or more prototypes are tested to clarify or redefine solution ideas. Testing involves soliciting the input of users, team members, and other stakeholders who have an interest in the finished product. It’s important at this stage to maintain an open-minded atti- tude toward accepting critique as the purpose of the testing process is to determine what will work and what won’t, before development begins.",
